<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-106-962  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 962.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  Dec 1989 v8 n12 p46(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computers: smaller, cheaper, faster. What more could an engineerwant?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Potter, Caren D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Design engineers have ever-greater computing power available atever-lower cost in personal computers (PCs), engineering/graphicsworkstations, minicomputers, 'near-supercomputers,' mainframes andsupercomputers.andP;  The systems are moving towards the use ofreduced-instruction-set computer processors, UNIX for a standardoperating system, and hardware architecture standards.andP;  PCs(microcomputers) used in design engineering are generally based onthe Intel 80xx6 or Motorola 680x0 microprocessors running,respectively, the MSDOS or Multifinder operating systems.andP;  Most PCcomputer-aided design (CAD) packages are designed to run onMSDOS-based systems.andP;  Use of each of the other computerarchitectures in design engineering, turnkey systems (hardware andsoftware sold together), and networking of design engineeringenvironments are also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer SystemsEngineeringDesignComputer-Aided DesignUtilizationApplicationsMarket AnalysisCriteria.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>